name: Paul Nicholas
summary: Eighties heartthrob Paul Nicholas appears notably different in his role as Major Gowen in the West End revival of "Fawlty Towers." John Cleese, the creator of the iconic comedy, believes that people who interpret jokes literally hinder comedy. Despite expressing that playing Basil Fawlty on stage would be physically demanding, Cleese is bringing the play to the West End. Cleese has made sarcastic remarks about the "Fawlty Towers" cast after observing their first rehearsal, while also expressing his preference for farce in theatrical settings. In creating the play, Cleese explained Basil Fawlty's socioeconomic status as lower-middle class. He also revealed that he had to remove racial slurs from the play due to concerns about people lacking an understanding of irony. Finally, Anne Hathaway discusses her latest film and shares anecdotes about Paul McCartney's Coachella performance and London's exclusive gentlemen's club, Whites.

summary: Legendary guitarist Duane Eddy, known for his distinctive echo-laden "twang" style, has passed away at the age of 86. As a pioneer of rock'n'roll music, Eddy's innovative guitar sound revolutionized the genre and earned him widespread recognition. His signature use of the "twang" technique, combined with his masterful fingerpicking, made him a visionary in the world of early rock music. Eddy's artistry contributed to the iconic soundtrack of the 1950s and beyond, cementing his status as a pivotal figure in the history of rock'n'roll.

name: The Idea of You
summary: "The Idea of You" has garnered positive reviews, with critics praising its delicate handling of age-gap romance. The Guardian portrays it as a "solid romance" that fulfills a fan fiction fantasy, while Empire commends its "deceptively courageous and perceptive" approach. Forbes breaks down the differences between the film and its source material. Evening Standard describes it as a "surprisingly enjoyable" rom-com, and TIME interviews the author, Robinne Lee, about fan fiction and women's art.
